Unknown Type.description: Willow Flycatchers have wider and whiter wingbars and a more greenish-olive cast than Western Wood-Pewees. They also have shorter wings and do not tend to sally to and from the same perch like wood-pewees do.

Dusky Flycatchers have a distinct eyering that Western Wood-Pewees lack, a rounded (not peaked) head, and a shorter bill compared to a pewee. Does not tend to sally to and from the same perch like wood-pewees do.
Olive-sided Flycatchers are larger than Western Wood-Pewees with a more distinct and well-delineated dark vest, contrasting strongly with a white center.
Eastern Wood-Pewees look nearly identical to Western Wood-Pewees, but breeding ranges hardly overlap and their calls are different, which is the best way to separate them.
Pacific-slope Flycatchers have a teardrop-shaped eyering not seen on Western Wood-Pewees and are more greenish-olive with a yellowish chest.
Cordilleran Flycatchers have a teardrop-shaped eyering not seen on Western Wood-Pewees and are more greenish-olive with a yellowish chest.
